            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Do you mean a specific “secondary agent” in a product or architecture, or do you mean the general concept? Here’s a concise summary of what a secondary agent can do in typical multi-agent systems:\n\nCapabilities\n- Execute delegated tasks: perform specific jobs the primary agent assigns (data lookup, formatting, calculations).\n- Specialize: handle domain-specific work (legal, medical, coding, analytics) that the primary agent delegates.\n- Run background/long-running work: batch processing, monitoring, scraping, or continuous model inference.\n- Orchestrate and integrate: call APIs, query databases, move data between services, and coordinate workflows.\n- Validate and test: check outputs, run unit or integration tests, and enforce correctness constraints.\n- Monitor and escalate: watch system health or task progress and escalate issues to humans or the primary agent.\n- Summarize and synthesize: compress logs, produce executive summaries, extract key facts.\n- Safety and filtering: enforce content policies, sanitize outputs, and perform checks for privacy/security.\n- Automate routine flows: send notifications, schedule jobs, and update records.\n\nTypical limitations\n- Needs explicit permissions/credentials to access external systems (APIs, files, databases).\n- Bound by platform capabilities (no internet access, limited compute, or rate limits).\n- Restricted autonomy: may require human approval for high-impact actions.\n- Privacy and policy constraints: cannot access or share protected data without authorization.\n\nIf you tell me which secondary agent or which system you’re asking about, I can list exact abilities, required permissions, and example tasks for that agent.",
